What is a dynamic block in Terraform?

Dynamic blocks generate repeated nested configuration blocks (like ingress, tag, setting) from a collection using a for_each loop, 
avoiding manual repetition when the number of nested blocks is variable.

Key Points (Interview-Ready)

• Used for nested blocks only
  - Not for creating multiple resources.
  - Use count or for_each on the resource itself to create multiple resources.

• for_each in a dynamic block
  - Accepts a list, set, or map.

• Inside the content { } block
  - <blockname>.value → Current element's value.
  - <blockname>.key   → Current element's key (for maps) or index (for lists).

• Dynamic blocks can be nested
  - A dynamic block can exist inside another dynamic block.
  - Keep nesting minimal to maintain readability.

• Best Practice
  - Use dynamic blocks only when necessary.
  - If the number of nested blocks is fixed, write them explicitly.
  - HashiCorp recommends avoiding overuse because it reduces code readability.

Interview One-Liner:
Use dynamic when you need to generate multiple nested blocks inside a single resource.
Use count or for_each when you need to create multiple resources.

Syntax

dynamic "block_name" {
  for_each = <collection>
  content {
    # use block_name.value or block_name.key here
  }
}
---

provider "aws" {
  region = "us-east-1"
}

variable "ingress_rules" {
  description = "List of ingress rules"
  type = list(object({
    port        = number
    protocol    = string
    cidr_blocks = list(string)
  }))
  default = [
    { port = 80,  protocol = "tcp", cidr_blocks = ["0.0.0.0/0"] },
    { port = 443, protocol = "tcp", cidr_blocks = ["0.0.0.0/0"] },
    { port = 22,  protocol = "tcp", cidr_blocks = ["10.0.0.0/16"] }
  ]
}

resource "aws_security_group" "web_sg" {
  name        = "web-sg"
  description = "Allow HTTP, HTTPS, SSH"

  dynamic "ingress" {
    for_each = var.ingress_rules
    content {
      from_port   = ingress.value.port
      to_port     = ingress.value.port
      protocol    = ingress.value.protocol
      cidr_blocks = ingress.value.cidr_blocks
    }
  }

  egress {
    from_port   = 0
    to_port     = 0
    protocol    = "-1"
    cidr_blocks = ["0.0.0.0/0"]
  }

  tags = {
    Name = "web-sg"
  }
}

resource "aws_instance" "web" {
  ami                    = "ami-0c101f26f147fa7fd" # Amazon Linux 2023, us-east-1 - verify latest
  instance_type          = "t2.micro"
  vpc_security_group_ids = [aws_security_group.web_sg.id]

  tags = {
    Name = "web-server"
  }
}

output "instance_public_ip" {
  value = aws_instance.web.public_ip
}
